default&#xa0;
default“No beha
defaultvioural impact is assumed over the forecast period as differences in rents will be small in the early years compared to the transaction costs of moving. The current estimate of the anticipated reduction in benefit expenditure is in the order of £400m in 20
default14/15 (real terms, 2012/13 prices).”
default&#xa0;
defaultWe are concerned that that given the costs of moving home and the lack of availability of affordable private rental properties, many families will reduce disposable income as a consequence of reductions in their LHA 
defaultpayments. This means that money intended to cover the costs of living is needed to cover shortfalls in assistance with housing costs.
default&#xa0;
defaultGiven the evidence that private rental prices are increasing faster than Housing Benefit rates, it is unsurprising that i
defaultt is becoming increasingly common for families to become homeless as a result of Assured Shorthold Tenancies ending and not being renewed.  
default&#xa0;
defaultThe table below shows the number of households accepted as being owed a main homelessness duty by their local auth
defaultority, who lost their last home as a result of the end of an Assured Shorthold Tenancy. The number have nearly tripled since 2010.
default&#xa0;
defaultFigure 3: households accepted as owed a main homelessness duty by the Local Authority who lost their last home as a result odefaultf the end of an Assured Shorthold Tenancy: 2010-2013default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultAs private sector housing is becoming increasingly unaffordable, access to social housing is also becoming increasingly limited. Numbers of households on social housing waiti
defaultng lists has increased by more than 800,000 since 1997, including a rise of around 100,000 since 2010 (see figure 4). 
default&#xa0;
defaultFigure 4: Local Authorities’ housing waiting lists 1997-2012default&#xa0;
defaultIt is crucial that the lowest income families a
defaultre able to afford the cost of their home. We are concerned that for those families on the very lowest incomes the increasing gaps between eligible rents for Housing Benefit and private rents, combined with increasing inaccessibility of social housing are t
defaultogether making housing unaffordable for many families with children. 
default&#xa0;
defaultDuring a recent debate in the House of Lords regarding linking the uprating of local LHA rates to CPI, Lord Freud committed to review the situation if local allowance rates and rents 
defaultbecome out of step
