defaultRecommendation 2: Given that around three quarters of those affected by the cap are children, it is particularly important that the review pays specific regard to the impact of the benefit cap on the well-being of children.  It is important that as part ofdefault this the review considers – default&#xa0;
default3. Localisation of support with housing costsdefault&#xa0;
defaultIncreasingly, support with housing costs is determined on a l
defaultocal, and discretionary basis. Local authorities have been provided with additional funding for Discretionary Housing Payments (DHP) to help deal with difficult cases caused by reforms, such as the benefit cap. Additionally, following the abolition of part
defaults of the discretionary Social Fund, local authorities have been allocated resources to introduce local welfare assistance schemes to provide support for families.  
default&#xa0;
defaulti. Discretionary Housing Payments default&#xa0;
defaultIn 2010/11 £20 million was available to local authorit
defaulties for DHP, this was increased to £30 million in 2011/2012 and £60 m illion in 2012/2013.  The 2013/14 allocation included an additional £30 million and £65 million to address the social rented sector size criteria and the benefit cap respectively, as wel
defaultl as £5 million to support the most sparsely populated areas. In 2014/15 The DHP pot available will be £125 million.
default&#xa0;defaultFigure 6: Discretionary Housing Payment funding (Great Britain) 2010-2015default&#xa0;
defaultClearly, local authorities have been given considerably more scope to address families housing needs on a local basis. The challenge is to ensure that this support gets to those families who need this most. 
default&#xa0;defaultRecommendation 3: The Department for Work and Pdefaultensions could do more to assist local authorities in advertising their schemes.default 
defaultThe gov.uk website should host links to all local DHP schemes in order to ensure that people looking to find out about their local scheme are able to find this online.default&#xa0;defaultLocal Adefaultuthorities should ensure that family information services are effectively communicating information about their local DHP scheme.default&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaultii. The introduction of local welfare assistance schemesdefaultFrom April 2013, crisis loans for living expenses and community 
defaultcare grants were abolished. Instead, funding was provided for local authority administered welfare assistance schemes.
defaultOur recent report 
defaultNowhere to turn
default 
defaultexamined the local emergency and community support now available through local welfare assistance sche
defaultmes. We found that the vast majority of the schemes are providing support for similar needs that were covered by crisis loans and community care grants. 
default&#xa0;
defaultA significant exception is that some schemes have stated that they will not be providing rent in adva
defaultnce. For example, Medway council states that their local welfare provision is scheme is “
defaultnot a rent deposit scheme or a rent in advance scheme
default” and Buckingham council’s
default scheme also states it does not provide this support.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe are concerned that the areas 
defaultwhere local welfare schemes do not provide support for rent in advance, families will find it more difficult to access permanent housing and this could lead to increased homelessness. Research from Crisis found that 69% of housing advisors who work in priv
defaultate rented housing access schemes have used crisis loans to fund rent in advance. As one housing adviser who responded to the Crisis survey said: “
defaultCrisis loans are absolutely vital in enabling clients to source rent in advance
default”. 
default&#xa0;defaultRecommendation 4: Local wdefaultelfare assistance schemes should make provision for rent in advance.default&#xa0;
defaultOur 
defaultNowhere to turn 
defaultreport also found that the majority of local schemes had some form of residency or local connection entitlement criteria. Around half of schemes indicated that the 
defaultclaimant needed to be resident within the borough. In three stricter cases claimants had to have been resident for at least a year before they could apply for help.
default&#xa0;defaultFigure 7: Local welfare assistance eligibility – residency criteriadefault&#xa0;
defaultReforms to housing 
defaultbenefit in both the private and social rented sectors are likely to lead to more low income households moving home and area. Our concern is that families will not be eligible for support through local welfare assistance schemes if they have to move to area
defaults with strict residency criteria. Only a small number of local welfare assistance schemes allowed claimants to apply for assistance if they were moving into the area or if they had a local connection, such as family living there. 
default&#xa0;
defaultSome schemes had excepti
defaultons to residency criteria such as families fleeing domestic violence, care leavers housed outside the local area or homeless households, but this was not universal. 
default&#xa0;defaultRecommendation 5: Local authorities should not set extended periods of residency before defaulthouseholds can get access to local welfare assistance.default&#xa0;defaultRecommendation 6: Exemptions from residency crdefaultiteria should be established,default specifieddefault and transparently communicateddefault for all local welfare assistance schemes.default&#xa0;default4. Housing support in Universal Creditdefault&#xa0;
defaultSupport with housing costs is radically changing as a result of the introduction of Universal Credit. Help with housing costs is rolled into the provision of other support. This will mean that a significant additional cohort of middle income renting famili
defaultes will receive support with housing costs.
default&#xa0;
defaultFor example, a single parent family with two children and with eligible rent of £100 per week would stop being entitled to Housing Benefit when the parent earned £395 per week (£20500 per year) or more. Under Un
defaultiversal Credit, they will continue to be entitled to receive some help with their rental costs with an income of up to around £655 per week (£34000 per year).
default&#xa0;
defaultThe introduction of Universal Credit will raise a number of challenges made all the more importa
defaultnt as a result of the increased cohort of claimants receiving help with their housing costs. This section will consider three issues in particular: 
default&#xa0;defaulti. Variations in work allowances by levels of housing costdefault&#xa0;
defaultIt has always been intended that under Universal Credit, households would have different levels of work allowances depending on whether they have housing costs. 
default&#xa0;
defaultHowever, initally, DWP stated there would be different levels of allowance for households wit
defaulth and without housing costs, with the level of "maximum" allowance reduced by 1.5 x the level of housing costs claimed, until it reached a "minimum" level.
default&#xa0;
defaultSo, for example, the "maximum" allowance for a lone parent with two children would be £8,800 per ye
defaultar, and the minimum would be £3,150.
default&#xa0;
defaultHowever, UC regulations now provide for only a maximum level of work allowance (for households without housing costs), and a minimum level (for those with housing costs). We are concerned this measure actually makes th
defaulte system considerably more complicated, since households with low levels of housing costs in receipt of UC would have to make a determination of whether they would be better off claiming for help with housing costs but receiving a reduced earnings disregar
defaultd, or making no claim for help with housing costs. For example:
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultRecommendation 7: There should be a minimum and maximum level of disregard, with the maximum reduced by 1.5 x the rate of housing costs until they reach the minimum ddefaultisregard.default&#xa0;defaultii. Housing costs for owner-occupiersdefaultAs with the current system, Universal Credit makes some provision for help with housing costs for home owners. We are very concerned by the "zero earnings rule" to be introduced within the Support for 
defaultMortgage Interest (SMI) regulations which mean that SMI can only be applied where the household is undertaking no paid work
default.  This is considerably less generous than the current system where the attachment of SMI to out of work income replacement benefits
default means that households may receive support on working up to 16, or in some cases 24, hours per week.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe regulations note that for those attempting part-time work, the removal of SMI will "
defaultin part be compensated by the operation of the full disregard
default".  H
defaultowever, for households undertaking very small amounts of paid work this compensation will be extremely limited, or non-existent.
default&#xa0;
defaultMany parents attempt part time work to keep labour market skills up to date and as a route back into long term employment, for
default example, parents who are disabled and are considering making a move back into work.
default&#xa0;
defaultThis new rule risks creating great complexity in accepting money for any period of employment, and creates an enormous “cliff edge” of entitlement.  In the worst cases, c
defaultlaimants may find that they lose very significant amounts of money as a result of taking on a couple of hours of work, and as a result losing their SMI entitlement.
default&#xa0;defaultRecommendation 8: Households earning up to the level of their maximum earnings disregard sdefaulthould be entitled to receive SMI payments as part of their Universal Credit claimdefault.  default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultiii. Direct payment to tenantsdefault&#xa0;
defaultUnder Universal Credit, payments for housing costs will normally be paid directly to the tenant (rather than to the landlord). This will
default be a significant change for many households living in the social rented sector who currently have payments made to their landlord.
defaultThe government believes this will promote financial capability and independence. However, we are concerned that some familie
defaults with children may struggle to manage their rental payments.
default&#xa0;
defaultOne survey
default found that 86% of social tenants believe “strongly” that it is better for housing benefit to be paid direct to the landlord and 35% were not confident that they can keep up rental p
defaultayments if they receive their rent direct.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultThe direct payments demonstration project has been established in six areas across Britain. In May, 17% of the total claimants had had their payments switched back to their landlord
default.
defaultAdditionally, concerns have
default been raised in the project review that the outcomes achieved within the pilot areas required resource intensive interventions and may not be scalable following the roll out of Universal Credit
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe government do acknowledge that some households will req
defaultuire alternative payment arrangements (APAs) for payment of housing costs. The current guidance on the application of APAs specifies two tiers of problem which would indicate claimants that are “highly likely” and those that are “less likely” to require al
defaultternative payments
default.
default&#xa0;defaultRecommendation 9: Claimants with a history of rent arrears, those with current rent arrearsdefault, and families that have previously been homeless should be considered “highly likely” to require APAs for their housing costs.default&#xa0;defaultRecommendation 10: The Local Support Services Framework for Universal Credit needs to ensure that sufficient support is provided to enable resource-intensive interventions from local delivery partners, to identify families that may require housing paymentsdefault made direct to landlords.default&#xa0;default27 September 2013default&#xa0;
